hat so and so thing taught \n=\r\n&gt; by Vishnu is superior to so and so thing taught by Shiva, etc. But we \n&gt; =\r\nknow that none of the hierarchies is absolute. \n&gt; \n&gt; One who has the nerve =\r\nto think that one can compare the wisdom of \n&gt; Jnaneshwar, dispassion of Ra=\r\nmana Maharshi, mad devotion of Ramakrishna \n&gt; Paramahamsa, detached activis=\r\nm of Vivekananda, compassion of Shirdi Sai, \n&gt; spiritual ecstasy of Vama Kh=\r\nepa, inner clarity of Lahiri Mahashaya, \n&gt; detachment of Trilinga Swami, pu=\r\nrity of Tukaram, humility of Eknath \n&gt; Maharaj, ecstatic love of Meera Bai,=\r\n motherly love of Gopaler Ma, etc, \n&gt; is a fool of the highest order. They =\r\ncan be compared from specific \n&gt; limited perspectives. In one thing, Tukara=\r\nm may be superior to all, in \n&gt; another Jnaneshwar, in another Trilinga, in=\r\n another Ramakrishna, and so \n&gt; on. You cannot compare in absolute terms. Y=\r\nou should not even try to. \n&gt; You should just appreciate them individually =\r\nand aspire to be like any \n&gt; of them that you like the most. \n&gt; \n&gt; Vimalana=\r\nnda&#39;s list may be correct from specific perspective. More \n&gt; importantly, h=\r\nis words should make one realize that there is always \n&gt; scope for further =\r\nself-control (and the resulting mastery over the field \n&gt; of duality) while=\r\n one is still embodied. One should never rest and \n&gt; aspire for better self=\r\n-control. But taking it as gospel and starting to \n&gt; judge yogis based on t=\r\nhat is unwise. Especially making statements like \n&gt; &quot;Vimalananda is heavier=\r\n than all RK&#39;s discples put togtr&quot; and thinking \n&gt; that something is absolu=\r\nte truth because Vimalananda is assumed to have \n&gt; said that (vs someone &quot;l=\r\nower than him&quot;) is unwise. \n&gt; \n&gt; Even if Vimalananda&#39;s hierarchy is absolut=\r\ne and universal, don&#39;t assume \n&gt; that you can judge the sta