ha and none less&nbsp;is a true Vigyani. He further=\r\n mentions that Swami Vivekananda did not (need) to&nbsp;go to the stage of =\r\na Siddha. His work was specific, he did the work and went off. He did not n=\r\need to and therefore did not&nbsp;become a Siddha. I see zero confusion her=\r\ne.&lt;/DIV&gt;\n&lt;DIV align=3Dleft&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVer=\r\ndana&gt;Added to this the fact that Vivekananda was very clear, just as all th=\r\ne disciples of Ramakrshna were clear, that Ramakrishna was a special spirit=\r\nual being, and higher than them. Here too I see no confusion.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P=\r\n&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DV=\r\nerdana&gt;&lt;&lt;It is not necessary that there is a clear order of greatness=\r\n. Infinity is neither greater than nor less than nor equal to infinity.&gt;=\r\n.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT si=\r\nze=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;This is what I call approximation. For an ordinary&nb=\r\nsp;man, all saints maybe equally&nbsp;elevated. For&nbsp;Yogis, there maybe=\r\n subtle differences and depths. The truth lies in the nuances.&nbsp;Anyway,=\r\n Vivekananda&#39;s own words are more reliable for me than yours on this matter=\r\n. And my previous explanation actually clarifies this statement of Sri Rama=\r\nkrishna that Vivekananda was the &quot;ancient Rishis Nara&quot; who came down for th=\r\ne good of mankind.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp=\r\n;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;&lt;Wise men tread cautiously an=\r\nd do not rush to judgment on others.&gt;&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 f=\r\nace=3DVerdana&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;\n&lt;P&gt;&lt;FONT size=3D2 face=3DVerdana&gt;I am merel=\r\ny quoting an